Name: JOSE AVILA
Title: Gate reader not working
Description: Gate reader not working
Solution:
These steps must be followed exactly as presented. These steps can be completed in as little as a minute. This will help minimize some of the issues with SNAPP and GateReader not communicating. Field Techs may say theres a DMA issue thats preventing the Gatereader from communicating with SNAPP. The DMA is an application adapter that links SNAPP with the GateReader. The steps below can resolve issues between SNAPP and the GateReader.

1.	Close the flight in SNAPP and then agent logoffs of SNAPP.
2.	Shut down SNAPP by clicking the X in the upper right hand corner of the SNAPP screen.
3.	Turn off the gate reader printer.
4.	Turn off the gate reader.
5.	Turn on the gate reader printer.
6.	Turn on the gate reader itself.
7.	Start SNAPP and then reopen the flight in SNAPP.
8.	Gate reader should work now.

Now dlterm launhes and gate reader should work

**Title from related Incident record IM2949787:
scanner not working Gate Reader
Solution:
Related Incident IM2949787 closed.
Research shows the gate reader was not properly intializing with SNAPP.  This is not a SNAPP attributable flight delay.
The steps to quickly recover the gate reader follow:  Do not reboot the work station unless the steps below fail.
These steps correct the problem 95% of the time and a reboot only corrects the problem about 5% of the time.

You must know where the power switches are on the gate reader printer and the gate reader itself to recover quickly.

1. Exit the flight in SNAPP and then logoff of SNAPP.
2. Shut down SNAPP using ALT+F4 or CTRL+ALT+F4.
3. Click YES to shut down all active browsers.
4. Turn off the gate reader printer.
5. Turn off the gate reader itself.
6. Turn on the gate reader printer.
7. Turn on the gate reader itself.
8. Start SNAPP and then reopen the flight in SNAPP.
9. If no test receipt, call the HELP DESK to create a ticket for the Field OPS Team to check the gate reader, gate reader printer,
   and the work station connections. Prepare to manually board the flight, via SNAPP.

Name: THOMAS STRAUB
Title: Gate reader not connecting
Description:
http://itkms.delta.com/Gatereader/Troubleshooting/EDB/00001.htm
Close out of SNAPP

Delta Proprietary Equipment:

Use ALT+F4 or CTRL+ATL+F4 to shut SNAPP down and restart SNAPP.

Common Use Equipment:

Instruct user to ALT+Tab | Click on Device Manager | Click on SNAPP icon | Choose Yes to Abort this instance of SNAPP
Have user log completely out of SNAPP and go back to the Common Use Airport Login Screen.

Power off the gate readers receipt iprinter (if one exists)


Power off the gate reader/scanner.


Power on the gate readers printer.


Power on the gate reader scanner.


Restart SNAPP and open the flight again, in SNAPP.


When the flight is open in SNAPP, try scanning a boarding pass.


If the boarding pass scans successfully, STOP HERE and continue with boarding the flight.


If the boarding pass did not scan successfully, use CTRL+ALT+Delete and then choose the LOGOFF option.  This is similar to a reboot, but is not a complete restart of the work station.


Go back to Step 6 and step through again.


If the boarding pass did not scan successfully, after the LOGOFF attempt, then the last course of action is to reboot the
workstation to recover the gate reader/scanner and scanner print device. This will take more than 6-10 minutes to reboot the
workstation and recover the gate reader/scanner.


After the reboot of the work station, Restart SNAPP, Log into SNAPP, and open the flight in SNAPP.


Scan the boarding pass again and if it scans successfully, STOP HERE and continue boarding the flight.


If the gate reader/scanner does not scan the boarding pass, after the workstation reboot, the agent has been advised to contact the help desk as it appears the gate reader hardware is malfunctioning.

Help Desk should verify the above steps were followed and if not, go back to step 1 and have agent perform steps 1-8 and continue with remaining steps 9-13 if the gate reader did not recover after the first 8 steps.

The SNAPP support team is trying to change the minds
Solution:
Related Incident IM2951781 closed.
replaced reader

Name: MELVIN TANKSLEY
Title: Gate Reader is not scanner Boarding Passes
Description:
Gate Reader is not scanner Boarding Passes
http://itkms.delta.com/Gatereader/Troubleshooting/default.htm
Use ALT+F4 or CTRL+ALT+F4 to shut SNAPP down and restart SNAPP.
Turn off the gate reader printer
Turn off the gate reader
Turn on the gate reader printer
Turn on the gate reader
Restart SNAPP and open the flight again, in SNAPP.
When the flight is open in SNAPP, try scanning a boarding pass.
If boarding pass scans successfully, STOP HERE and continue boarding flight
If boarding pass did not scan successfully, use CTRL+ALT+Delete, then choose LOGOFF option. This is similar to a reboot, but is not a complete restart of the work station so much faster.
Repeat steps 6&7.
If boarding pass did not scan successfully, the last course of action is to reboot workstation to recover gate reader/scanner & scanner print device. This will take more than 6-10 minutes to reboot & recover gate reader.
After reboot of workstation, Restart SNAPP, Log into SNAPP, & Open flight.
Scan boarding pass again and if successful, stop here & continue boarding.
If gate reader/scanner does not scan the boarding pass, after workstation reboot, & following steps above, engage ODS . If ODS is unable to resolve,
User wants to get a ticket, for FO instead of ODS since this is the last flight
user stated that they have a work around for the issue until FO comes out

user did reboot computer power cycle the gate reader , it is working fine now but user still requesting tech to check it
**Title from related Incident record IM2964253:
gate reader is not working
Solution:
Related Incident IM2964253 closed.
Research shows the gate reader dropped the connection to SNAPP.  This is not a SNAPP attributable flight delay.
The steps to quickly recover the gate reader follow:  Do not reboot the work station unless the steps below fail.
These steps correct the problem 95% of the time and a reboot only corrects the problem about 5% of the time.

You must know where the power switches are on the gate reader printer and the gate reader itself to recover quickly.

1. Exit the flight in SNAPP and then logoff of SNAPP.
2. Shut down SNAPP using ALT+F4 or CTRL+ALT+F4.
3. Click YES to shut down all active browsers.
4. Turn off the gate reader printer.
5. Turn off the gate reader itself.
6. Turn on the gate reader printer.
7. Turn on the gate reader itself.
8. Start SNAPP and then reopen the flight in SNAPP.
9. If no test receipt, call the HELP DESK to create a ticket for the Field OPS Team to check the gate reader, gate reader printer,
   and the work station connections. Prepare to manually board the flight, via SNAPP.

Name: KURT STORM
Title: Gate Reader Printing Passenger Itineraries Instead of Boarding the Passenger
Description:
http://itkms.delta.com/Gatereader/Troubleshooting/EDB/00030.html
Click the VIEW tab, just below the SNAPP Version, in the upper left hand corner of the SNAPP screen.


Click on the Gate Reader option in the drop down menu.




Click on the Down Arrow, on the far right side, of the Operating Mode line in the resulting Gate Reader Management pop up.




Scroll down in the operating mode menu. Click on Service Recovery and SAVE button. (This puts the gate reader into Service Recovery mode).




Repeat Steps 1-3 to get to the Operating Mode drop down menu again and continue with Step 6 below (do not repeat step 4 above)..


Agents should click Turbo and then click the SAVE button.




Scan a boarding pass. The passenger should show as ON in the SNAPP seat map and not print the passenger's itinerary.

IF THIS ISSUE HAPPENS AGAIN:
Shut down SNAPP immediately with CTRL+ALT+F4 or ALT+F4
Power off the gate reader printer.
Power off the gate reader.
Power on the gate reader printer.
Power on the gate reader.
Restart SNAPP and open the boarding flight.
Scan a boarding pass and it should show the passenger as ON the flight.
If the itineraries still print, agents must reboot the work station.
If the reboot does not correct the problem, open an Incident Ticket to AO - Airport Systems SNAPP Web

**Title from related Incident record IM2980562:
Flight Delay - Gate reader not working
Solution:
Related Incident IM2980562 closed.
Research shows the gate reader dropped the connection to SNAPP.  This is not a SNAPP attributable flight delay.
The steps to quickly recover the gate reader follow:  Do not reboot the work station unless the steps below fail.
These steps correct the problem 95% of the time and a reboot only corrects the problem about 5% of the time.

You must know where the power switches are on the gate reader printer and the gate reader itself to recover quickly.

1. Exit the flight in SNAPP and then logoff of SNAPP.
2. Shut down SNAPP using ALT+F4 or CTRL+ALT+F4.
3. Click YES to shut down all active browsers.
4. Turn off the gate reader printer.
5. Turn off the gate reader itself.
6. Turn on the gate reader printer.
7. Turn on the gate reader itself.
8. Start SNAPP and then reopen the flight in SNAPP.
9. If no test receipt, call the HELP DESK to create a ticket for the Field OPS Team to check the gate reader, gate reader printer,
   and the work station connections. Prepare to manually board the flight, via SNAPP.

**Title from related Incident record IM2988165:
Flight Delay - Gate reader is not working - not registering boarding passes
Solution:
Related Incident IM2988165 closed.
Research shows the gate reader dropped the connection to SNAPP.  This is not a SNAPP attributable flight delay.
The steps to quickly recover the gate reader follow:  Do not reboot the work station unless the steps below fail.
These steps correct the problem 95% of the time and a reboot only corrects the problem about 5% of the time.

You must know where the power switches are on the gate reader printer and the gate reader itself to recover quickly.

1. Exit the flight in SNAPP and then logoff of SNAPP.
2. Shut down SNAPP using ALT+F4 or CTRL+ALT+F4.
3. Click YES to shut down all active browsers.
4. Turn off the gate reader printer.
5. Turn off the gate reader itself.
6. Turn on the gate reader printer.
7. Turn on the gate reader itself.
8. Start SNAPP and then reopen the flight in SNAPP.
9. If no test receipt, call the HELP DESK to create a ticket for the Field OPS Team to check the gate reader, gate reader printer,
   and the work station connections. Prepare to manually board the flight, via SNAPP.

The steps to quickly recover the gate reader follow:  Do not reboot the work station unless the steps below fail.

3. Click YES to shut down all active browsers.
4. Turn off the gate reader printer.
5. Turn off the gate reader itself.
6. Turn on the gate reader printer.
7. Turn on the gate reader itself.
8. Start SNAPP and then reopen the flight in SNAPP.
9. If no test receipt, call the HELP DESK to create a ticket for the Field OPS Team to check the gate reader, gate reader printer,
   and the work station connections. Prepare to manually board the flight, via SNAPP.

For SNAPP attributed flight delays include all the information outlined on this page and PNR examples (or customer name and flight number or seat number), flight information, SNAPP version number on upper left corner of screen, workstation name or WSINE, function performed and problem/error response. This helps the SNAPP team in their research to resolve issues and defects.
**Title from related Incident record IM3026903:
Flight Delay - gate reader issue
Solution:
Related Incident IM3026903 closed.
Research shows the gate reader dropped the connection to SNAPP.  This is not a SNAPP attributable flight delay.
The steps to quickly recover the gate reader follow:  Do not reboot the work station unless the steps below fail.
These steps correct the problem 95% of the time and a reboot only corrects the problem about 5% of the time.

You must know where the power switches are on the gate reader printer and the gate reader itself to recover quickly.

1. Exit the flight in SNAPP and then logoff of SNAPP.
2. Shut down SNAPP using ALT+F4 or CTRL+ALT+F4.
3. Click YES to shut down all active browsers.
4. Turn off the gate reader printer.
5. Turn off the gate reader itself.
6. Turn on the gate reader printer.
7. Turn on the gate reader itself.
8. Start SNAPP and then reopen the flight in SNAPP.
9. If no test receipt, call the HELP DESK to create a ticket for the Field OPS Team to check the gate reader, gate reader printer,
   and the work station connections. Prepare to manually board the flight, via SNAPP.

**Title from related Incident record IM3036928:
Gate Reader
Solution:
Related Incident IM3036928 closed.
CUTE work stations cannot use the instructions as shown in this problem report.  Those instructions are only for Delta Proprietary work stations.  The only recourse CUTE locations have to to shut down the SNAPP application and restart their Delta Air Lines session on the CUTE work station.  This is the only manner to recover a gate reader at this time.

Title: Gate Reader takes too long to scan boarding passes
Description:
Gate Reader takes too long to scan boarding passes...Need some assistance
**Title from related Incident record IM3039249:
Gate Reader takes too long to scan boarding passes
Solution:
Related Incident IM3039249 closed.
Research of the work station shows this is an ongoing problem created by two separate data collection tools installed on Delta Air Lines proprietary work stations to collect system information.  These two applications will take up too much CPU resources and this is the reason the gate reader is scanning slowly.   This is not a SNAPP issue and the problem cannot be corrected until after the summer season.   At this time, there is nothing that can be done to prevent this gate reader slow down from happening.
